[3
Date: 2 Sep 2000 17:57:35 +0200
From: Dan Michaeli <michaeli@netvision.net.il>

West Nile virus Fever in Israel
-------------------------------
A report issued by Dr Rishpon (District Health Officer in the MOH) on 31
Aug 2000 about a meeting at the MOH, includes the following highlights
about West Nile virus (WNV) in Israel. So far [the MOH [has received
reports of 12 human cases with 2 deaths of elderly patients (more than 80
years) this year. Since the beginning of the year there [has been
laboratory confirmation of 23 cases, 14 in the month of August. [This
increase is attributed to [an increase in the rate of positive results and
not to the number of samples. Testing for WNV was not routine for several
years but was resumed in Jan 1999, and serological surveys conducted since
then [indicated that infection was prevalent among veterinarians and geese.
In a survey of 300 reserve soldiers, conducted in 1987 by the Army only 7%
of the 20-30 age group were seropositive. This finding is in accordance
with the present findings that WNV, which was relatively common in the 50's
to the 70's, became more rare until recently. Both the Ministry of Health
and the Ministry of Agriculture are taking measures to monitor and contain
the disease which is not considered a major public health threat at the
present time.
--
Dan Michaeli MD
Clalit Health Services
101 Arlovorov st
Tel Aviv 62098 , Israel
<michaeli@netvision.net.il>
[Although West Nile virus is endemic in the Middle East, knowledge of the
epidemiology of West Nile virus-associated disease and human immune
responses to infection is relevant to understanding of the outbreak in
North America. This thread will be continued but restricted to
consideration of these issues. -Mod.CP
